(a) Is he aware that - (i) invasive aquatic plants have grown in many tanks in Sri Lanka currently; and (ii) the tanks have got filled due to organic sediments that get deposited in the river beds when these plants decay?

(b) Will he inform this House - (i) whether there is any programme to remove the invasive plants in the above tanks; (ii) the programme which is implemented to renovate the tanks which have got filled by now; and
(iii) whether a programme will be formulated in collaboration with the Farmers Associations to eradicate the invasive plants that grow in tanks?
(c) Will he also inform this House -
(i) the steps that have been taken to protect the tank reservations and the dams; and
(ii) whether steps will be taken in collaboration with the public to protect tanks?

PRODUCTION OF VEGETABLE SEEDS IN GREENHOUSES:
asked the Minister of Agriculture and Plantation Industries:

(i) whether he is aware that the Agriculture Instructor of Kundasale sought the approval of the Ministry of Agriculture in 2018 to prepare a suitable programme for the production of vegetable seeds in greenhouses as a solution to the problems arising in the production of vegetable seeds due to weather changes in each cultivation season in Sri Lanka;
(ii) the action taken by now in that regard;
(iii) whether it is expected to get the involvement of the greenhouses owned by the private sector in the above programme; and
(iv) if so, the methodology adopted in getting the involvement of the aforesaid greenhouses in the programme mentioned above?

( ) (The Hon. Eran Wickramaratne) Sir, I rise to a point of Order. Again, I am raising this issue under Standing Order No. 47, which states, I quote:
47. (1) The question shall be put by the Speaker and the votes may be taken by voices, Ayes and Noes, and the result may be declared by the Speaker.

(2) Any Member who is not agreeable with the decision of the Speaker may call for a division for a vote to be taken in any of the following methods as may be determined by the Speaker. In such case the division bells shall be rung for five minutes and thereafter -
(a) a division shall be taken by counting the
(b) a division shall be taken by the use of the
electronic vote recorder. The Members shall press the appropriate button to indicate the decision of such Members within the time period allowed by the Speaker;

Sir, I am bringing this up because yesterday, in violation of the Standing Orders, a Vote was not taken. I must make a correction here that any Member of Parliament can ask for a Vote. If a leader of a party brings in a proposal, that does not mean that everybody is obliged to follow that and say there is no need for a Vote. There can be a dissenting vote. Any Member can actually ask for a Vote and the Vote should be given. It is very unfortunate that the Hon. Speaker

Our demands are as follows, I quote:

1. We demand the world, the key role players of the global politics to look at the root-cause of the issue of the Mediterranean region and to find ways of practical actions to treat this problem immediately by implementing the right and genuine solution of creating and recognizing the independent and sovereign State of Palestine of 1967 Borders with East Jerusalem as its capital. This will be the only way to achieve stability and a justifiable peace in the region and the world must act to ensure that Israel must accept the same.

2. We demand to stop the war immediately and to come to the table of negotiations to fulfil the stressing need to implement the universally agreed Resolutions, the international laws and the decisions made in this regard. The international community to fulfil their obligations to the maximum level to support the creation of the Independent State of Palestine.
3. Israel should be held accountable under international laws and the universal humanitarian regulations for the blatant war crimes that they commit now and before alike.

4. As Members of Sri Lankan Parliament, we appeal the United Nations and all its agencies, international community, all governmental and civil institutions, NGOs, INGOs and all civic-minded citizens of the world, those who love and seek peace in the world to swiftly act by taking necessary steps to be imposed on Israel to stop its onslaught oppressions and aggressions against the people of Palestine.

5. We humbly appeal to the western countries especially the three Permanent members of the UN Security Council USA, UK and France to stop supporting Israel and apply fair play in keeping with international law without hypocrisy and double standard.
This is the time to be honest and genuine, especially when it comes to dealing with human values, human rights for people to live in dignity and peace."

Sir, the letter that had been sent in this regard to the UN Secretary-General had been signed by more than two-thirds of the Members of this Parliament, which adds up to 156 Members, comprising of former Presidents the Hon. Mahinda Rajapaksa and the Hon. Maithreepala Sirisena, the Leader of the Opposition Hon. Sajith Premadasa and prominent leaders and Hon. Members from various other political parties.
We stand for the truth and may justice prevail!

.. ( .. ) (The Hon. G.G. Ponnambalam) Hon. Presiding Member, I am thankful and happy that my good Friend the Hon. Dilan Perera is present here when I am speaking because he is the Chairman of the Sectoral Oversight Committee on Reconciliation and National Unity.

Sir, I wish to bring to the notice of this House an incident that took place on the 05th of November, last Sunday. A group of students from the Jaffna University travelled overnight to Batticaloa District to support some livestock farmers protesting with regard to the grazing lands in Mailaththamadu and Madhavanai as they are unable to use those grazing lands to feed nearly 300,000 cattle because of illegal settlements; corn cultivators from the Polonnarurwa District have been allowed to settle in those grazing lands. As a result, there is a conflict that is going on and those livestock farmers have been protesting for almost a month now. So, those students had come down from Jaffna and joined the protest. It was a token protest. They had joined the protest right through the morning and had decided to carry out a small procession. The police were also present. When those students had decided to carry out a small procession, the OIC of the Sandiweli Police Station was also present and had cooperated in guiding the students in that procession.

The police had given advice that the students must not block the road. So, they were only on one side of the road, very methodically carried on the procession for a few minutes and thereafter, had broken up very peacefully and non-violently. There was no traffic at that time also. So, they had broken up, had had some cool drinks, had shared it with the police and eventually got into the bus and left to go to Jaffna. Several minutes after they had left, about 10 to 15 minutes afterwards, they found that the police were chasing after them. The police had chased after them, stopped them and went on to arrest six individuals saying that they had carried out an illegal procession without permission.

Hon. Presiding Member, we all know of the provision with regard to having to inform the police in advance for a procession to take place. But, by not doing that, it does not become an illegality. The reason why they ask to inform the police in advance is simply because the police can then regulate traffic, if, in case, there is going to be a traffic jam. That is the reason, not to inconvenience the public. But, the police were already present at that protest. So, there was no question of them not knowing in advance. The Traffic Police were also present and, in fact, they cooperated. Then, why is it that, after this procession was done, the students were suddenly chased behind and eventually arrested? I tell you, Hon. Presiding Member, it was because of the senior officials of the Batticaloa Police Station. SSP Amal Edirimanna was the chief culprit. It was he who had put pressure on the Sandiweli Police to arrest them as he had been, in turn, put political pressure because nobody wants Mailaththamadu and Madhavanai cattle farmers to succeed in their protest; they want to weaken them. As a result, they do not want others coming from outside districts to help these protestors and strengthen them.

Now, Sir, I want to ask this. Those students were arrested and were kept overnight. It was only subsequently that they were released on bail. So, is what the students did an offense? Is that something for which you arrest those students? Do students not have the right to protest? Is it not freedom of speech that is being violated? So, how on earth, Sir, would you expect the Tamil people to stay silent when they are being battered by various ways in which their rights are being denied to them? How can those farmers exist in todays economic situation, if they are not able to graze their cattle in those lands? They have not been able to use those grazing lands for months now because of fear; the army and the police threaten them and they fear for their lives. Their cattle are being destroyed; grenades are put in the mouths of cattle and are being destroyed! There is evidence of that all over the place. So, why is this happening, Sir?

In the same district, you have a Buddhist monk, Venerable Ampitiye Sumanarathana Thero, who threatens to cut Tamils into pieces! But, nothing is done in that regard. Carrying out a peaceful procession with the help of the police is a crime, but when a monk threatens to cut Tamils into pieces, being violent not only to the police, but to government officials, the general public and the

Tamil people, nothing happens! So, how on earth would you think that this country is going to reach reconciliation? How on earth would that happen? And it is in this police that you are asking us to repose our trust in order to get justice. For Gods sake, Sir, this is the reality to which this House has to wake up.

Resettlement of Protracted IDPs of the Northern Province:
Muslim people forcibly evicted from the Northern Province in 1990 have now been gradually resettled in their places of origin in all five districts.

Further, most of the displaced persons settled in Puttalam District, who were given a deadline in 2018 to return to their original places, have returned within the time frame. Thus, as of today, there are no more protracted IDPs to be resettled in the Northern Province. This fact is confirmed by all the five District Secretaries of the Northern Province and also by the District Secretary of Puttalam.

A report obtained from the Director, Resettlement Division of the Ministry of Urban Development and Housing is annexed with the details of (a) resettled families and (b) families to be resettled with the housing requirement in the Northern Province. However, it is noteworthy that some of the displaced Muslim persons have permanently settled in the Puttalam District.

With regard to the land gazetted as forest and wildlife reserves in 2012 as mentioned in the Motion, the Hon. President has directed at the meetings held on reconciliation matters to consider the release of reserved land based on the 1985 maps. Following Cabinet approval - Cabinet Paper No. 23/1090/613/008, dated 2023.06.08 - a series of discussions was arranged with the relevant officers at the district level to identify the areas reconsidered for release. Similarly, a discussion was held on 19.08.2023 in Mannar District with the Chairman of the DCC, Hon. K. Kader Masthan, MP, where the Hon. Rishad Bathiudeen, MP was also present.

It was agreed to have a special meeting for Musali GN Division which includes the villages Marichchikkatti, Karadikkuli and Palaikkuli, as mentioned by the Hon. Rishad Bathiudeen in his Adjournment Motion, in order to review the areas gazetted and consider their release on the basis of the justification of their settlement and other livelihood activities. A table with details is given below:

According to the Divisional Secretary, Musali, 484 LDO permits have been issued to the resettled families from 2009 and 4,806 houses have been provided for the families from 2009 to 2021. However, there is a need to provide 401 houses. Further, 621 families have been identified as landless.

The Divisional Coordinating Committee will recommend this requirement to the DCC with justification to be considered under the proposed housing scheme and degazetting of land identified from the forest and wildlife areas. The reports from the DS, Musali are also given as Annexes.

The Motion moved by Hon. Rishad Bathiudeen and seconded by the Hon. H. M. M. Harees will be referred to the Hon. President to appoint a Presidential Commission to look into those issues and address them.
